How do we get our rate-limits lifted on Nineteen.ai? We are increasing our hosted validation footprint, and multiple subnets have Nineteen.ai as a requirement, so we understandably hitting rate-limits.
Thank you!

@bruhvatar [τ, τ] @Presario [τ, τ]

Issue: In a single epoch image miners plummet in rank because they incur multiple “-2” penalties, even though their image similarity is high and should be accepted.

Root cause: I think there is a bug in the scoring mechanism for image, the validator compares its own NSFW flag on the expected image against the miner’s NSFW flag:

```
if expected_image_response.is_nsfw != image_response_body.is_nsfw:
    return -2
```
https://github.com/rayonlabs/vision-workers/blob/11d865cbe3d5505d18fa38e3e8d3069d0de93830/validator_orchestrator/app/checking/functions/image_based.py#L95

But the NSFW model is **not** perfectly stable. All the optimizations done by the miner can flip its decision, ive seen it quite some times happening now over the last two weeks, so the miner gets unfairly punished. Even though the image similarity is perfectly fine..

The fix is easy: Always calculate `is_nsfw` flag on the actual miner output rather than using the validator’s `expected_image` NSFW flag. This ensures the same image is judged consistently and should eliminate these sudden -2 drops.

Thoughts?

It also makes sense in the way the output works, you are not showing the "expected_image" to the end-user, you are showing the miner's output, so the calculation should be done on that actual output imho. Also due to the nature of all the optimizations we are doing to get Flux way under 1000ms, the nsfw check should actaully be completely moven to the validator side, or we should pick a much more stable NSFW engine that doesnt do a coinflip 🙂
for proof, happy to share audit reports in pm 🫡

essentially as a miner you would be more inclined to maximise the weight set for your UIDs by a validator with high alpha stake, as they have a higher say in the final weights set across miners: https://taostats.io/subnets/19/distribution

The organic_validator should verify if the resolution is part of `cst.ALLOWED_AVATAR_RES` for avatar requests and `cst.ALLOWED_TEXT_TO_IMAGE_RES` for image_to_image requests. # Press Release

**Subnet 19 Transitions Ownership to Taostats**

It is with a mixture of pride and sadness that we announce the sunsetting of Subnet 19 as a collaborative effort between Rayon Labs and Taostats. Moving forward, full ownership and responsibility of Subnet 19 will return to Taostats.

From its inception, Subnet 19 broke new ground. It pioneered stable incentive mechanisms that became the blueprint for many subnets to follow. For a time, it played a vital role in showing how Bittensor could grow, and its contributions helped lay the foundations for today’s thriving ecosystem.

Subnet 19 has reached a natural end in its current form. We believe the slot it occupies should be used for something that contributes fresh value to Bittensor rather than detracting from it.

Rayon Labs has decided to dedicate its energy to Chutes and Gradients, two subnets that push the boundaries of distributed compute and showcase the immense potential of Bittensor in delivering meaningful AI solutions. These projects now carry the mantle of innovation once borne by Subnet 19. To ensure a smooth transition, all Corcel and nineteen functionality is now available through Chutes.ai, and anyone with an API key is encouraged to migrate over as soon as possible. Work is being done to ensure any balances previously added will be transferred over to chutes.

In the meantime, Taostats/ will assume full stewardship of Subnet 19. Effective immediately, burn code will be implemented while the future direction of the subnet is determined. A customary key swap will also take place in the coming days, purely as a security measure. Once a new vision is clear, the community will be the first to know.

Though this chapter is closing, we want to acknowledge the joy, pride, and professional growth Subnet 19 has brought to those involved. It was a space of experimentation, learning, and collaboration that we will always hold with gratitude.

This is not the end—it is a turning of the page. Subnet 19’s legacy lives on in the broader ecosystem, and the next chapter promises to be every bit as impactful. We look forward to sharing more in due course and thank the Bittensor community for its continued support and belief in what we are building together.

— **Taostats & Rayon Labs**

Here is the issue: recently, we've had at least one, probably more, pump-and-dump scams (cf: 46).  I know that's not you.  However, what it means is that we updated the requirements for running a channel here to **both** being the owner of the subnet **and** having GitHub code that people can use.  The idea here is: since this server's subnet channels are for miner/validator support, if there is nothing to support, there's no need for a channel.  Otherwise, it becomes the domain of token speculators/investor support, which we can't support here.

Once you have code ready to support operations, of course there will be a channel for it.

I'll have to discuss with the rest of the team whether there's a middle ground possible, which is for known actors (such as Taostats) to talk about development. Normally we don't provide incubator spaces, which is what that would be, and there would be a double-standard if we allowed some people to do it, and didn't allow others.  That's why I personally prefer that projects start on *testnet*, because in that case, I can happily set up a testnet channel for them so that they can work on testing & development with the community (and gather a community who's familiar with the code), and when they're ready to operate on mainnet, the transition is much easier.

It's a challenge with people who've obtained an existing subnet and announce that they've done so, however, because at that point, I'm not sure how you would prevent people from taking your testnet code and trying to run it on mainnet (though if you're burning all the miner emissions, as you say, that would hopefully act as a deterrent).
